The first virtual operator will arrive, this year, in the Czech Republic.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
Probably won't be long before he gets here.
That Czech operators are part of the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it in mobil.cz.
The rest also confirmed that the Czech Telecommunication Office (ČTÚ) warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the whole Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulating roaming rates, a paradoxical situation is likely to be reached - for some customers of Czech mobile operators the SMS they send from abroad will be cheaper than if sent from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, as we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to regret that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, also said that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market led to a significant price decline, to which classic operators also had to react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the market in Britain, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It was shown that there is room for such operators and that they can succeed.
Otherwise, there is no need to look for examples too far.
In February of this year we informed you about the premiere of the Mobilking virtual operator in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to obtain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking is the Penta group which, besides that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is in the possibility of focusing on many more specific target groups.
In addition, for them to be able to function effectively, many fewer customers are enough than a classic operator.
They do not bear relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators usually profile themselves with low costs - they offer cheap SMS calls and messages that, however, are often offset by the more adjusted service offer.
Thus, for example, mobile tesco in Britain offers SMS at least half cheap with respect to competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good hit the bet for a trivial goal group.
This operator specifically addresses the man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - is the operator who likes and who you can trust," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept like that of Poland could be attached to our country.
He doubts Vodafone's spokesman, Miroslav Čepický: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the supply of services is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if in the Czech Republic there will be any virtual operator that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech R. it does not seem too hopeful.
Rather, this is the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region," he said in telephone conversation for mobil.cz, Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
Indirectly he said that the current mobile telephony operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
Rather the contrary, they try to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competition arises.
Interest in launching a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step forward to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, so that we can offer our customers not only fixed telephone services but also mobile phone services.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have met repeatedly with all Czech mobile telephony operators.
With some of them we have made progress in the meetings," said the spokesman for the group, Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe they'll unlock better times.
It appears that, by informal information, the first official operator would possibly have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now its appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"We now believe that the situation is suitable for the emergence of a virtual operator on the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this field," he said to mobil.cz, Vlastimil Sršeě, spokesperson for Telefónica O2.
Other operators refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokesperson Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with O2's opinion, adds: "To date we have not registered any viable commercial projects that, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to be developed."
He adds: "In the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find a virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this point we should already have on the table a specific contract that could be studied on such a short horizon."
Vodafone focuses rather on meeting the requirements of a 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of spending and infrastructure sharing.
It is precisely considered as the greatest contribution from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a quick internet on the mobile."
Responsible offices - with the operators nail and meat
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition, which would lead to a price drop and thus a decrease in profits.
Then why facilitate entry into the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull out the same rope, proof of it is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on ČTÚ was at the time of U:fon's entry by T-Mobile society.
It is witnessed by public information accessible on the ČTÚ websites.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds: "In addition, the competitive environment on the mobile phone market has not been open to a fourth operator in a long time.
As regards the character of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would mean for him and, above all, for his services great requirements."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging because of the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not just the position of ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Licitations (UOHS).
However, it expressed its typical stance on this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after a contract on the rental of the necessary infrastructure was concluded between a mobile telephony operator and a virtual operator.
So far no agreement has been closed since the offer of potential stakeholders was not interesting enough for classic operators," he added to our question Kristián Chalupa, from the ÚOHS Department of External Relations.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For the offices that must represent the interests of consumers it is more than just a consideration, besides that they must note that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the foreign country where virtual operators operate normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the price drop in mobile telephony services"
Evidently, pressure on the proper functioning of the market media and price drops do not fall within the interest of UOHS.
The dramatic shock in this whole case lies in the dissonant reactions resulting from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence, is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline in the gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a tough struggle for competition.
"The Office in this regard has not found any signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore, they have no corresponding rise in responsibility in their market operations.
The tools needed to open the mobile telephony market to virtual operators, rather, are lacking, as well as telecommunication regulators," Chalupa added to his response.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is obviously an analysis of relevant markets developed by the ČTÚ according to which telecommunications is from the point of view of the commercial tender a single market.
In this type of market, none of the Czech operators naturally has a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile phone operator - with all his logic - has the monopoly of his network.
Therefore, in a specific segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument was not accepted, at least for ÚOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators are strikingly ascending in a similar way.
The current complaints of the interested parties (including the GTS Novera company) show that in all negotiations with the operators there are many similar impediments.
Carrying responsibility in ČTÚ is a rather common trick in the field of telecommunications of which ÚOHS washes hands in this whole matter.
We've already met him in similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the Telecommunications Act was recently tabled for the extension of ČTÚ's competition in the field of commercial tenders that did not take effect, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
The representatives of ÚOHS must know this perfectly, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
It's all right, when no one looks.
At the same time, something like a pseudovirtual operator that already exists in the Czech mobile telephony networks remains unnoticed.
They are companies that put their own prices to mobile telephony services which, however, only a part are public.
Usually these are companies that are engaged in multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only some of the chosen ones get the price list of these companies.
The magic is in that the company, with regard to the operator, acts as a classic business client of the company in charge of a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile telephony operators prohibit such resale.
"If such cases as those cited could be discovered, we could talk about breaches under contract conditions that could be translated into the end of collaboration with the given society," she answered the question about this problem Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity carried out by mobile telephony operators would not reach responsible people.
It is precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned above that it can become thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they get no negligible profits and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of possible problems: "the law allows for such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a despised so much percent of customers.
These, in addition, must accept that your phone's SIM card is not in your name so you cannot absolutely have it as a normal customer of the operators."
This is precisely what the ČTÚ should think of as minimally strange.
There is also a new question for ÚOHS.
If mobile phone operators turn their eyes around in this type of procedure, why do they block the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that ÚOHS has sufficient competence to discover such activities and if it is not to want it should not be satisfied with the operators' explanations that they have no idea of this history and that their trading conditions do not allow it.
When we'll stop being the most expensive
As was already clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a significant decline in service prices.
At the same time, in practically all the countries where the virtual operator emerged, classical operators tried to protect themselves from this outbreak.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market, eventually, too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, regulatory bodies have now intervened and in none of the cases defended the operators but their customers.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure they got the first virtual operator to emerge and with him they started to emerge more.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body all of this case happens as if it were a burning nail.
Because of our experience, we can only be impressed that the confusion of the powers in these cases suits them.
But don't despair.
If this information between frames is correct and the virtual operator actually reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market will probably start moving again.
If one of the operators lets a virtual mobile phone operator in, it will be difficult for the ÚOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech hymn has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four presentations of the new version of the Czech official hymn.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the day of the Czech official celebrations presented the new official recording of the Anthem Where, my home.
The new hymn was recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bęlohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solos, one by male voice and one by female voice, one with Coro and another instrumental.
Kateřina Knęžínková and Adam Plachetka are responsible for singing.
The authors of the anthem's arrangements are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
The iHNed.cz server can hear the four versions.
Bęlohlávek considers this national Czech song as one of the most beautiful hymns.
The Czech Radio already said earlier that intentionally he chose for the singers Solos with representatively young voices that are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I have tried with both and then, also, with the Choir that would be set in the diction so that the text would be well understood, so that it would be consistent," he commented.
The Czech official hymn celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, my Home played for the first time in 1834 in the tables of the State Theatre in the original Czech work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetan Tyl and arranged with the music of František Škroup.
He won popularity and people made it his.
The first strife of the song after the rise of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became, naturally, a part of the official hymn.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
