Prague MHD takes us Wednesday for the first time with the chip
On Wednesday, October 1, 2008, it is written in the history of the Prague Transport Company that the first passengers enter the subway, the tram and the bus with an electronic bonus in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
This can now be acquired by nearly one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy the 30-day, 90-day bonus and the annual bonus (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously load it on their chip card at the information centers and positions of the transport company at the stations of the Metro, Muzeum, Męstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Andęl, Roztyly, Letjany, Kobylisy, Rajská Zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Bonds can already be purchased from yesterday on the Internet on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until afternoon, was used by more than four hundred people.
Those who start using the Internet as a form of trade can definitely start forgetting the ticket sales positions at the subway stations, where so far they had to regularly line up to get a normal ticket.
The bonus is purchased online, and the Opencard card is reloaded to you in one of the 13 branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places there is available to passengers a window with prepared personnel that helps interested parties with the purchase on the internet and also with the recharge of the bonus purchased on their card," said project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to recharge the electronic bonus on the Opencard on the automatic vending machines found in some lobbys of the subway.
What are these vending machines like?
They are red, they remind us of a ticket pickup machine and the travelers will probably have already fixed on them at the stations of the metro of Roztyly, Budęjovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are now five in the city but at the end of the year there would have to be eighty," Opatrný completed.
The bonus is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
The use of the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Enter the Opencard chip card into it and the previously paid bonus will be charged only on it.
Electronic bonds from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
That is to say, on the bypass trains and bus lines from the numbers 300 to 499 that mainly use the inhabitants of the towns of central Bohemia.
"On trains attached to the integrated transport of Prague there are reviewers equipped with a reader card that will help to confirm the validity of the time and the area of the bonus," explained the control of the tickets, Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid that sets the schedules for the collective transport of Prague.
Bypass buses have their reader cards mounted in the driver's locker.
When entering it is necessary not only to show the card to the driver but also to accompany it with the Opencard at the place intended for it on the side of the Box.
With this, the driver controls the validity of the bonus.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the bonds there is nothing easier than requesting this information from the driver," completed Drapal.
Passengers who do not travel on bypass buses and do not remember when the bonus expires may address the vending machines where the cards are reloaded.
Here, on the machine screen, you will be shown the information about the validity of your document.
