If we can't be part of Germany or Austria, we want to at least live under the patronage of the United States of America.
With this desire, some German groups from the Sudetes were presumably directed to the president of the United States in 1945.
It results from the letters that are stored in a particular archive and that are now stored in the collection of the Scientific Library of South Bohemia.
The Germans of Český Krumlov request in a letter to the American President that they do not allow the return of the "land Šumava" - occupied by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Pact - again to Czechoslovakia.
"We have correctly understood the situation and we really want your word that American units are arriving in German lands not as oppressors or enemies but as liberators" is written in the letter, signed with a "people who carry the fate of Šumava in their hearts."
