"We cannot believe that without considering the opinion of four million people, we are given to a foreign state that oppresses and rejects minorities and that in no way collaborates with the victory of the allies," the letter writes.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is presumably the fear of reprisals of the "Czech oppressors".
If the U.S. president presumably questioned this idea of the Shumavo Germans, it would be enough to organize a referendum on the Shumavas lands about whether their inhabitants want to be part of the U.S. or live under their patronage.
