The interview - Blood is safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated his tenth anniversary of his foundation yesterday, and his president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has once again become one of the safest and most effective providers of blood in the world.
And above all, he regained the public's confidence that he had seriously been hampered by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and the discontent of the public, in February 1994 the Canadian government conducted a public survey, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations for such a disaster to be reproduced no longer.
While Judge Krever took time to present his relationship, certain provinces then set up a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee carried out this mission.
As a result of the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Hema-Quebec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Society of Blood to supply all other provinces and both territories.
" In 1998, when Hema-Quebec began its activities, nearly 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, recalls Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
After having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work during the years that followed, we have recovered the public's confidence," he says before proudly affirming that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebequesa population had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary recalls that "confidence is extremely fragile. "
Since its establishment, on 28 September 1998, Héma-Quebec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we attended in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of the disease of the crazy cow, a new variant of the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, counts Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
Then we support one of the main recommendations of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, according to which when we do not know it and when a serious disease can emanate from it, in this case the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob that is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we introduce measures of exclusion.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of those who had remained in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been proved beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted by the blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle applied had the meaning. "
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique for HIV detection appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests that allow the presence of the virus to be detected directly in the blood of donors, rather than antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
Nucleic acid tests allowed to shorten the period between the time when the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
We could reduce this period by less than a week.
We thus substantially reduce the risk that certain donors will be infected without knowing and that we will not be able to detect them.
These improvements significantly reduced the risk of AIDS by blood transfusion.
Today, one person every 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"That means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Héma-Quebec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood products every year, it will pass more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission comes through a blood product.
I believe that today you can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without concern," says Héma-Quebec's head of management.
" Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of the Reunion, which, as an example of the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
Be constantly vigilant, " Dr. Décary seeks to stress that in addition to safe supply, Hema-Quebec must also provide sufficient supply.
" Needs increase because the population ages.
Since the most aggressive anticancer treatments, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
Population ageing also has consequences on the network of blood donors, which on average regroups only 3% of Quebequeses eligible for blood donation. "
All people with good health, 18 years old and corresponding to eligibility criteria, however, can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who propose their blood are not accepted because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they travel in a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
The hardships are very rare.
But members of this donor network need to be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and to encourage them to be a regular donor.
Since today's life is very unbridled, we rarely find the time to spend an hour donating his blood, " Francine Décary is afflicted.
With a budget of $297 million per year, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was formerly considered as biomedical waste is filled with a rich blood of stem cells that can be used for the treatment of serious diseases such as leukemia.
" We have celebrated a few weeks ago, the putting on the bank of our millennium blood sample from the umbilical cord, and it is expected to take out more than a thousand of these a year.
We should begin to propose it for grafts at the beginning of next year, " says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood taking program as very popular.
" Many mothers are disappointed in not being able to enjoy this, " as Hema-Quebec has no resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
