Following an Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold claims that the world's largest gold company attempted a six million-euro defamation process against three authors and a small publishing house in order to trigger a " transparent public debate " .
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation persecutions, but the law.
No surprise, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to harm anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to his?
The outcome of the litigation is of little importance, the authors and the publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defence and to fight, with very uneven weapons, against an army of lawyers held by the almost unfunded pockets of the mining company.
The tactics, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly arrangement that will numb the opposition in addition to scaring whoever dares to consider the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it's in front of the public opinion that he would have had to present his vision of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several countries where Barrick Gold works, discussions in Canada are usually done by changing ideas and not by clawing.
It was enough for the mining company to open its books, records and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the financing of independent search teams that could have clarified the issue.
But Barrick Gold doesn't seem to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and support letters for Noir Canada's authors.
Could Mr. Garver possibly explain how he can call for a "public" debate by disrespecting his views?
According to the Vice-President, it seems that this word designates only highly paid lawyers and not all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
In democracy, detractors also have the right to speak.
What you don't understand - or what you don't want to understand - Barrick Gold, is that the public who holds the authors and the publishers of Noir Canada does it above all because it rejects the brutal manner of the mining company.
This audience is willing to listen to Barrick and judge him, but on the basis of civilized changes in arguments, and not in the context of what many people perceive as a persecution-moderacy (assuring the " public debate " , Barrick Gold has just made a request with regard to the authors of Noir Canada urging them not to use this word anymore).
In addition to Mr. Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's process is a direct attack on freedom of university search and truth, essential to all democratic societies.
It denies the right to cite credible sources and to have a debate on facts and interpretations, which represent the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects who dislike rich companies in this world in a country like Canada, under the penalty of many persecutions, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, he could do so in accordance with the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
You have a right of reply.
The university world, to which we belong, has long known how to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's merciless persecution clearly shows that, contrary to what he intends, he has no desire to make a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the university world, but also for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to place devices that limit this genre of abusive persecutions.
Wall Street rescue operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and Congress leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most important economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the 700 billion-dollar plan that seeks to curb the financial crisis that has shocked Wall Street for months has yet to be confirmed by both Houses of Congress.
In particular, I envisage: better control by the elect of their implementation, new mechanisms that seek to ensure the reimbursement of public invested money, new provisions to contain the number of houses not paid, as well as a right of control over wages paid to the leaders of the assisted companies.
The American Secretary of the Treasury, Henry Paulson, the president of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, at the end of a marathon of Che negotiations lasted two days.
" We make great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets, " said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
" Everything has been done to cover the economy and ordinary Americans in the face of the current Wall Street crisis, " explained the Democrat.
" It is the fundamental point: if we do not do this, trauma, chaos and disturbances over the daily lives of Americans will be immense, " said Republican Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had been over very quickly in the last few hours because they feared the effect that would lead to a new failure in the mood of investors.
The last time they had been set was the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates in the American presidential elections, who have acceded late to the negotiations, were rather favourable to the agreement, however, without forgetting to express their discontent to be forced to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama gave him certain arrangements to reach the agreement, particularly that which would allow the owners to retain their domicile and that on the salary of the leaders of the surviving companies by the State.
" When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no need to congratulate themselves.
But these measures are necessary, " he commented on American television.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, interrogated in another chain to know if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied that: "I would like to see the details, but I hope to vote for it. "
" The important points I read show that it is something that we will have to digest and with which we can advance.
He said that the option of doing nothing is not acceptable. "
The 700 billion plan aims to buy with taxpayers' money doubtful debts, assets at risk and inventible from American financial institutions.
It arrives after 14 months of a crisis caused by the outbreak of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risk mortgage credits before extending to other more common forms of credit securities (PCAA) and causing a liquidity freeze and a disbanding of banks and financial institutions.
It is a group of elected Republicans who had changed the first draft agreement last week.
We believe that we have left the stalemate since the Democrats accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
With the aim of tackling the hardships for everyone in Congress, we also added a provision that stipulated that if the government had to assume losses for five years with this program, it could impose new fees that would seek to help him recover money.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first part of 250 billion, to which an additional 100 billion can be added if the president thinks it is necessary.
