What were they producing in the Zuschlag &amp; Co. invoice factory?
Very soon, on 8 October, the criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of committing fraud of significant damage, in a business manner, continuously and in an organized manner, in addition to other crimes, including the falsification of documents.
According to the Office of the Prosecutor, the funds obtained in public competitions were used for their own purposes, justifying on many occasions the performance of tasks with false invoices.
The public funds and that of the town councils - in total about 65 million HUF - stopped in part in the Treasury of the Fiatal Baloldal organization and in part in the pocket of individuals.
The method, which was also announced by the researchers, was to justify the collection of funds obtained in the public competitions with false invoices behind which there was no actual execution, the various associations never fulfilled their assumed obligations.
According to the charge, most of the bills were false.
To this end they obtained the talonaries in the market of the District of Józsefváros and the circular stamps were manufactured in the city of Kiskunhalas.
And the question that on behalf of which company the counterfeit invoice was to be made was decided among others on that tour of the Higher Region of the Balaton where János Zuschlag sent to István Lados.
The latter confessed that for this purpose I should choose hostels and restaurants.
He asked for an invoice for his consumption and they served as a model for making the invoices he presented, among others, in the competitions of the Ministry of Youth and Sports Affairs, the Ministry of Social and Labour Affairs, as well as the City Council of the Capital.
These bills were mostly signed by István Lados and his accomplice András ěri, who according to our information rather wrote the reports necessary to obtain public subsidies.
During one of his "study trips" sides he chose a brewery.
According to two invoices issued in 2003 by Zuschlag and its accomplices, this gastronomic center provided food for a group of ninety people from the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
However - according to the centre manager - so many people do not fit at the same time in that place.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 for the Jobb Jövőert Foundation - later called Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért - was filled with formal and contextual errors.
For a hostel in the town of Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms and more than ten people could not stay there in one night, yet on the bill there were one hundred and thirty people.
But the big fantasy bill manufacturers also exaggerated when they pointed to the gastronomic center Pigal Kft. For in the books of it - according to the information given to the Prosecutor's Office - there were no documents on behalf of Jobb Jövęert and Hoppá.
The company's manager, Gyęzę Farkas, informed hvg.hu that when he was quoted by the prosecutor's office and showed him the bills, he knew that they were false documents.
"In the seal the name of our company and the NIF appeared in the wrong place."
He added: In addition to the formal problems he did not agree that according to the bill 100 people were housed, since they have only eleven rooms in which so many people do not fit.
In addition, the bill also included meals, while the restaurant has not been working for a long time.
The enthusiastic invoice manufacturers were also not informed that the travel agency chosen in Budapest exclusively organizes trips abroad, so that in the cash payment invoice they foolishly indicated a trip within Hungary as a service, which also did not coincide with the agency's invoice issuance practice.
Furthermore, as was known during the investigation, VAT was included in the document, even though travel outside the territory of the European Union was tax-free.
Among other things, the VAT measure was also incorrect in the four documents issued by the Hotel Révfülöp Kft. for the Jobb Jövęért Foundation, since the services of that company are not charged with a 25 but only with 15 percent VAT, in addition the employees of the hotel only extended invoices made by machine, however the invoice was manual.
In addition, the "expeditors" also made other mistakes, such as in the case of a company in which they put in the invoice as an activity carried out by road transport to which - it was known during the investigations of the prosecutor's office - does not perform the company founded as an investment consultant.
Similarly, due to formal differences - inappropriate format of the invoice, false seal - it was found that the invoices issued for Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, for XXI. Szazadi Kulturális Egyesület and for Biztos Pont.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfeher Sports Camp, whose representatives denied having issued those bills.
The counterfeiters also did not pay attention to the fact that when Fiatal Városért Egyesület's group ate there (2001) the HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in the process of liquidation, so he was responsible for the liquidation process - according to our information - refused to have issued such a document.
They consciously issued the bills
Another group of counterfeit invoice manufacturers are made up of those who were aware that they should issue fictional invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifju Szocialisták, issued an invoice worth about four million HUF on behalf of the Együtt Foundation to Harmadik Évezredért.
The Collab Kft manager - according to the charge - was convinced by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi, to issue fictional bills.
Similarly, he collaborated with Zuschlag and his accomplices the Biogate Kft., currently under the liquidation process, which in 2003 provided invoices of approximately five million HUF to the Jobb Jövęert Alapítvány Foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the Vörösfenyę Egyesület association, without real economic activity behind it.
There was no movement of capital either, as they later cancelled the prepared invoices but forgot to record this entity's documents.
The next group of counterfeit invoice manufacturers includes those who have some connection with the defendants.
Thus, for example, Iván Kubatov was the defendant of the Ukrainian Delta Trio SL manager with a fictitious headquarters in Budapest, who dealt with the trade in fuels and vehicles.
This company issued numerous invoices of approximately HUF 18 million in the months of October, November and December 2005 on the sale of computer media.
According to the investigation data, these invoices were purchased by the Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which since 14 September 2005 is under liquidation process.
The company's manager was a Romanian to whom Iván Kubatov should have also sent the documents related to the company between 2002 and 2005.
We have information that Kubatov recognized during the investigation that he issued on behalf of the company invoices for the Atlasz, for the Hoppá and for Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány by collecting the amount himself.
Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt. were founded by Romanian masons at the express request of Iván Kubatov.
None of the companies, however, actually worked because - according to the defendant - they did not get a job.
But he benefited from these companies, since at the request of his accomplice, counsel Zsolt Szente, who prepared the company's registration documents, issued invoices on behalf of the companies for the organizations linked to Zuschlag: for the Atlasz and for the Y-Generació.
Kubatov, on behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, gave a total of 15 invoices to different entities worth 14.2 million HUF.
The Office of the Prosecutor considered that Kubatov received VAT and 10% of the amount of the invoices.
That man even took advantage of the society in command Szi-Beri to issue fictional bills used in the Biztos Pont contest.
The Y-Generació and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországégért presented a competition in January 2006 to Tancs Mihály Alapítvány (TMA), a publicly useful entity of the Socialist Party.
They obtained 500,000 HUF from the contest, respectively, but did not use the money for the contest's objectives.
For this not to be discovered, they submitted to TMA five fictitious invoices received from the Works Team Kft.
These were the invoices found during the registration of the office that Arpád Kemecsei had at the headquarters of the Ministry of Education.
Some of the defendants will probably relate in the trial - as they did in the Office of the Prosecutor - the course of counterfeiting of invoices.
The most interesting thing may be the confession of Chief defendant János Zuschlag himself, if he decides to dismantle everything.
For his confessions so far have not been very detailed and although he repeatedly promised to talk about everything, this has not done so until now.
The question is: what interest does it have?For perhaps in exchange for the return of most of the money - 50 million HUF - the socialists came to an agreement with him for Zusi to assume all the responsibilities.
Who, on the other hand, for these days could even be offended, since in order to alleviate his prison conditions requested house arrest, but was repeatedly denied.
While the many perpetrators of highly valued economic crimes, who never returned the money, walk freely or at least can wait in their own home for the sentence, he has no chance for that.
Psychology of overlapping: Why do we spend more money?
The auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
New York University neurologists and economists discovered the neurological - economic bases of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to the study in Science magazine, people do not want to lose in competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" through experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played lottery, the other participated in an auction and in the meantime it was examined through the functional magnetic resonance system (fMRI) the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games the participants could earn money, but during auctions, where it is essential to bet more than the other, when the game was lost, the functioning of the complex called strata located under the brain cortex was intensified.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self prize" of the nervous system.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in betting is explained as a prevention in order not to provoke an intense reaction of the strata.
To substantiate their theory, the scientific group economists also carried out a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups bet against one person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
In addition, another group was promised that if they win, they would receive another $15 more prize.
Instead, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in the event of losing the auction the group members lost even that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, by verifying the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the group who played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winner" group.
"These results cannot be deduced from any existing economic theory previously.
For those so far explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped solve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation" - Andrew Schotter, professor of the New York University's economics faculty, established.
Hepatitis: When should you go to your doctor?
In the world some 500 million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the main causes of death.
The number of contagious people in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated because many of the patients do not know they are infected.
The name of hepatitis is the common name of different liver diseases caused by viruses.
Symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogenic agents and disease caused are very different.
Hepatitis viruses that depend on the pathogen are spread through two main forms: hepatitis A and E by food (e.g. with water or contaminated food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body humors (sperm, vaginal humor, saliva).
Travellers are recommended to be protected by vaccine against virus A and B, against C there are no vaccines.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two or three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifested by means of a general condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, it appears in the skin and in the white eye, the jaundice, the excrement becomes clear, the dark-coloured urine and the healing can last up to two - three weeks.
Annually a million people die in the world in cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to the calculations, only one in ten contagions receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can cause liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most infected people do not know that they are ill because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms appear only 20-30 years later.
Premature recognition, systematic medical control, is therefore very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and those who wear tattoos.
There are currently some 200 million people in the world suffering from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with routine laboratory control as well, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing some unknown symptoms.
The disease has healing if discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus of the organism, so that contagion can be suppressed and cancer prevented.
On September 30 is the World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and to the importance of premature recognition.
Does it hurt less who believe in God?
According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith has a calming effect that also alleviated the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Oxford University scientists conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed religious belief in how it influences human pain - reported British newspaper Telegraph.
In the framework of this unique experiment they applied electrical shock to 12 Catholic believers and to the same number of atheists, while all were looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the technique of scanning the human brain, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
This experiment is the first in the series of research in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University also participate alongside academics.
The analysis took place as follows: they fixed a sparkling instrument on the patient's left hand, which applied the electrical shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look at two paintings; the Virgin Mary, the work of Sassoferrato of the 17th century, and the Lady of the 15th-century Bedroom of Leonardo da Vinci.
The researchers had the hope that the show of the Virgin Mary would provoke a certain religious spirit among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and they thought it had a reassuring effect.
Patients spent half an hour in a MRI scanner, receiving 20 electrical shocks in four successive parts during that period while watching the painting of religious subject or the other one.
Catholics claimed that when they looked at the Virgin Mary, they felt in "security" as "protected" people, "satisfied and peace reigned in their hearts."
Watching the religious theme picture, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias who also participated in the experiment thinks that with any such shocking image you can get a similar effect with the atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person they feel very positively about, like a mother or a father," the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright celebrated the outcome of the investigation.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases really change our personality," added Wright.
After these formidable results, there is only one question: what effect would it have on the regulation of pain if the Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of his size were shown to the faithful?
Would the vision of a high quality Virgin Mary bring even better results?
