Járóka: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today the European Summit for Equal Opportunities has been launched in Paris, its host is France, which is also the European Union's turn-in president this year.
Livia Járóka, Member of the European People's Party for the Fidesz, in her message to the plenary, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations that plague Roma children and is also the biggest obstacle to the prevailing of their interests.
This high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs and by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
The meeting was attended by representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the most important European organisations for the protection of social rights.
Járóka - according to the press office of the Fidesz group in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to discrimination in employment, Roma are left out of the labour market first because of their low level of schooling.
"Most of the young Roma have not finished secondary education and because of the poor quality of basic education, only a small part can obtain a university diploma."
Járóka further stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, has a decisive role to play in the prevalence of other human rights as well.
Investment in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise a broad awareness of these issues both among the Roma and among the non-Gypsies.
For the sooner a Gypsy student starts school, the more possibilities it will have to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to quality education and ensure the abolition of segregated and low-level education" - Livia Járóka stressed.
According to the MEP, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary to speed up the school disaggregation processes immediately, and it is essential that the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives be properly complied with.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, we must offer Roma children the possibility that guarantees democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as citizens of full rights," Járóka demanded.
The objective of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities organized annually since the Berlin meeting last year, which was held in the sign of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities", is to ensure a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at the European and national level of the Member States.
